.TH BURROW 1 "2026-04-13" "burrow" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
burrow \- personal task catalogue, runner, and scheduler
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B burrow
.RI [ subcommand ]
.RI [ arguments ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B burrow
is a personal task OS: a single place to catalogue, run, log, and schedule
your scripts.
It is global-first (lives in
.IR ~/.config/burrow/ ),
catalogue-first (tasks have names and descriptions, not just commands), and
log-first (every run is recorded with full stdout/stderr).
.PP
Running
.B burrow
with no arguments launches the interactive TUI.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
.B burrow
Launch the TUI (default when no subcommand is given).
.TP
.BI "burrow run " task
Run
.I task
headlessly.
Output is streamed to stdout/stderr and the run is recorded in history.
If the task has
.B depends_on
entries the full pipeline is resolved and executed in order before the
requested task.
.TP
.B burrow list
Print all configured tasks as plain text, suitable for scripting.
.TP
.B burrow init
Scaffold
.I ~/.config/burrow/tasks.toml
with a starter template and open it in
.BR $EDITOR .
Does nothing if the file already exists.
.TP
.B burrow daemon <subcommand>
Manage the background daemon.
See
.B DAEMON SUBCOMMANDS
below.
.TP
.B burrow help
Print a summary of usage and keybindings.
.SH DAEMON SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
.B start
Enable and start the burrow daemon service.
.TP
.B stop
Stop the running daemon.
.TP
.B status
Show daemon status, uptime, heartbeat, and next scheduled run times.
.TP
.B install
Write the platform service file (systemd unit on Linux, launchd plist on macOS).
.TP
.B uninstall
Remove the service file.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Burrow merges two config files:
.TP
.I ~/.config/burrow/tasks.toml
Global catalogue.
Always loaded.
.TP
.I ./burrow.toml
Local, repo-scoped catalogue.
Loaded when present in the working directory.
Local keys override global keys of the same name; tags and env vars are merged.
.SS Settings
.nf
[settings]
max_parallel = 4              # max concurrent tasks
log_dir      = "~/.config/burrow/logs"
max_log_run  = 500            # prune history after N runs per task
max_log_age  = 90             # prune history older than N days
.fi
.SS Tasks
.nf
[tasks.db-seed]
cmd         = "node scripts/seed.js"
description = "Seed the development database"
cwd         = "./backend"
env         = { NODE_ENV = "development" }
tags        = ["db", "setup"]
depends_on  = ["other-task"]   # run other-task first (pipeline)
on_failure  = "notify-slack"   # task name or shell command on failure

[[tasks.db-seed.inputs]]
name    = "target"
prompt  = "Which environment?"
options = ["dev", "staging", "prod"]   # omit for free-text

[[tasks.db-seed.inputs]]
name   = "confirm"
prompt = "Confirmation message"
.fi
.PP
Commands are executed via
.B /bin/sh \-c
so shell features such as
.BR $VAR
expansion, pipes, and redirects work as expected.
.PP
Each
.B inputs
entry prompts the user before the task runs and injects the value as an
environment variable named by
.IR name .
Omit
.B options
for a free-text prompt.
Use
.B $name
inside
.B cmd
or
.B env
values to reference the collected value.
.SS Schedules
.nf
[schedules.nightly-seed]
task = "db-seed"
cron = "0 2 * * *"            # standard 5-field cron expression
.fi
.SH TUI KEYBINDINGS
.TS
l l.
\fBKey\fR	\fBAction\fR
\(ua/k	Navigate up
\(da/j	Navigate down
r	Run selected task
x	Kill running task
l	Clear log view
Tab	Switch pane tab (tasks / schedule / history)
/	Fuzzy filter by name or tag
a	Add task
e (tasks tab)	Open task source file in $EDITOR at the task definition line
e (schedule tab)	Edit schedule cron expression inline
Enter/Space	Toggle schedule enabled/disabled
D	Clear task history (history tab)
?	Toggle help overlay
pgup/ctrl+u	Scroll log up
pgdn/ctrl+d	Scroll log down
q/ctrl+c	Quit
.TE
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/burrow/tasks.toml
Global task catalogue.
.TP
.I ./burrow.toml
Local repo-scoped task catalogue.
.TP
.I ~/.config/burrow/history.db
Run history stored as a bbolt embedded database.
Do not edit directly.
.TP
.I ~/.config/burrow/logs/
Per-run log files, named by task and timestamp.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B EDITOR
Used by
.B burrow init
to open the config file after scaffolding, and by the
.B e
keybinding (tasks tab) to open a task's source file at its definition line.
.SH EXAMPLES
Launch the TUI:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
burrow
.EE
.RE
.PP
Run a task headlessly and pipe its output:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
burrow run db-seed | tee /tmp/seed.log
.EE
.RE
.PP
List tasks, then filter with grep:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
burrow list | grep db
.EE
.RE
.PP
Check daemon status:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
burrow daemon status
.EE
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR cron (8),
.BR systemctl (1),
.BR make (1)
